Lymph nodes are small, bean-shaped structures that are part of your body's immune system. They help fight infections by filtering harmful substances. Fibromatosis colli is a condition that affects babies. It happens when a muscle in the neck becomes thicker than usual. This can make it hard for the baby to turn their head to one side. Muscle atrophy in the neck means that the muscles in your neck have become smaller or weaker than usual. Myositis ossificans is a condition where bone tissue forms inside your muscles after an injury. Imagine your muscles are like soft, stretchy rubber bands. A cervical muscle spasm is when the muscles in your neck tighten up suddenly and you can't control it. This can make your neck feel stiff or sore, and it might be hard to move your head. Torticollis is a condition where your neck muscles cause your head to twist or tilt to one side. It might feel like your neck is stuck or stiff, and it can be uncomfortable. Cervical nerve root compression means that the nerves in your neck are being squeezed or pinched. This can happen because of things like a slipped disc or bone spurs. A brachial plexus lesion is when the group of nerves in your shoulder area, called the brachial plexus, gets damaged. These nerves help control your shoulder, arm, and hand movements. Glossopharyngeal neuralgia is a condition that causes sudden, severe pain in the back of your throat, tongue, or ear. Phrenic nerve palsy is when the nerve that helps your diaphragm move doesn't work well. The diaphragm is a muscle that helps you breathe by moving up and down. Accessory Nerve Palsy is a condition where one of the nerves in your neck, called the accessory nerve, isn't working properly. This nerve helps control some of the muscles in your shoulder and neck. The vagus nerve is like a messenger in your body that helps control things like your heart rate, digestion, and even your voice. A lesion on this nerve means there is some damage or problem with it. Cervical plexopathy is a condition where the nerves in your neck are not working properly. These nerves are important because they help control your shoulders, arms, and hands. Your doctor can help figure out why this is happening and what can be done to make it better.

A cervical sympathetic chain schwannoma is a non-cancerous growth that develops on the nerves in your neck. A parathyroid adenoma is a small, non-cancerous growth on one of your parathyroid glands. These glands are located in your neck and help control the amount of calcium in your blood. Hyperplasia of the parathyroid means that the parathyroid glands, which are small glands in your neck, have grown larger than normal. These glands help control the amount of calcium in your blood. When they get bigger, they might make too much of a hormone that can cause your calcium levels to rise. This can lead to problems like feeling tired, having weak bones, or even kidney stones. It's important to keep an eye on this condition to make sure your body stays healthy and balanced.

Parathyroid carcinoma is a rare type of cancer that affects the parathyroid glands. These glands are small and located in your neck, and they help control the amount of calcium in your blood. When someone has parathyroid carcinoma, it means that there are cancer cells growing in these glands. This can cause problems because it might lead to too much calcium in the blood, which can make you feel tired, weak, or have bone pain. It's important to talk to your doctor to understand more about this condition and what can be done to help.

A parathyroid cyst is a small, fluid-filled sac that forms in the parathyroid glands, which are tiny glands in your neck that help control the amount of calcium in your blood. These cysts are usually not harmful and often don't cause any symptoms. Most people don't even know they have one unless it's found during a test for something else. If the cyst is small and not causing any problems, doctors usually just keep an eye on it. If it gets bigger or causes symptoms, they might suggest treatment.

Parathyroid hyperplasia is when the parathyroid glands, which are small glands in your neck, become larger than normal. These glands help control the amount of calcium in your blood. When they get bigger, they might make too much of a hormone that increases calcium levels. This can lead to problems like weak bones, kidney stones, or feeling tired and weak. It's important to keep an eye on your calcium levels and talk to your doctor about any symptoms you might have.

Ectopic parathyroid tissue means that some of the parathyroid glands, which are small glands in your neck that help control calcium levels in your body, are not in their usual place. Normally, these glands are located behind the thyroid gland in your neck. However, sometimes they can be found in other areas, like the chest or near the heart. A pharyngeal diverticulum is like a small pouch or pocket that forms in the throat area. Imagine if your throat had a little balloon sticking out. Hypertrophy of the pharyngeal tonsils means that the tonsils in the back of your throat are larger than usual. These tonsils are part of your immune system and help fight infections. Tonsillar asymmetry means that one of your tonsils is bigger than the other. Tonsils are small, round pieces of tissue at the back of your throat that help fight germs. The pharyngeal wall is a part of your throat that helps you swallow and breathe. Sometimes, this wall can become thicker than usual. Pharyngitis is when your throat gets sore and scratchy because it's inflamed. This can happen if you have a cold or an infection. You might feel pain when you swallow, and your throat might look red. A peritonsillar abscess is like a pocket of pus that forms near your tonsils, which are the two small lumps at the back of your throat. This can happen when a sore throat or tonsillitis gets worse. Tonsillar calcifications are small, hard deposits that can form in the tonsils, which are the two small glands located at the back of your throat. These deposits are usually made up of calcium and other minerals. They are not harmful and often don't cause any symptoms. Sometimes, they might cause a feeling of something stuck in your throat or bad breath. It's like having tiny stones in your tonsils. A salivary gland stone is like a tiny rock that forms in the tubes that carry saliva in your mouth. Saliva is the liquid that helps you chew and swallow food. Sometimes, minerals in the saliva can stick together and form a stone. This stone can block the flow of saliva, causing pain or swelling in your mouth or under your jaw. Sialadenitis is a condition where your salivary glands, which help make saliva in your mouth, become swollen and sore. This can happen because of an infection or a blockage in the glands. A parotid gland mass is a lump or bump in one of the salivary glands located near your jaw, just in front of your ears. A mucocele is like a small, harmless bump that can form in your mouth, usually on the inside of your lip or cheek. It's caused when saliva, the liquid in your mouth, gets trapped under the skin. This can happen if you accidentally bite your lip or if a small salivary gland gets blocked. Mucoceles are usually not painful, but they can feel a bit strange. A submandibular gland tumor is a growth in one of the glands under your jaw that makes saliva. Saliva is the liquid in your mouth that helps you chew and swallow food. You have a small stone in one of the glands under your tongue. These glands make saliva, which helps you chew and swallow food. A parotid cyst is a small, fluid-filled sac that forms in the parotid gland, which is one of the salivary glands located near your jaw and in front of your ears. Salivary gland atrophy means that the glands in your mouth that make saliva are getting smaller or weaker. Saliva is the liquid that helps you chew, swallow, and digest food. A lipoma is a soft, fatty lump that grows under your skin. It's made up of fat cells and is usually harmless. When it happens in the neck, it might feel like a small, squishy bump. A hemangioma is a kind of birthmark made up of extra blood vessels. When it's on the neck, it might look like a red or purple bump or patch on the skin. A cervical abscess is like a pocket of pus that forms in the neck area. It happens when bacteria get into the body and cause an infection. This can make the neck swell and feel sore. Sometimes, it might be hard to move your neck or swallow. It's important to see a doctor because they can help drain the pus and give medicine to fight the infection. A branchial cleft cyst is a small, soft lump that can appear on the side of your neck. It's something you might be born with, but it can take years to notice. A sebaceous cyst is a small, non-cancerous bump under the skin. It forms when a gland in your skin gets blocked. This can happen anywhere on your body, but in this case, it's on your neck. A soft tissue sarcoma in the neck is a type of cancer that starts in the soft tissues, like muscles or fat, in the neck area. It is not a common type of cancer. A cervical cystic lesion is a small, fluid-filled sac that can form on the cervix, which is the lower part of the uterus that opens into the vagina. Fat necrosis in the neck means that some of the fat tissue in your neck has been damaged. This can happen if you've had an injury or surgery in that area. Cervical fibrosis means that the tissue in the cervix, which is the lower part of the uterus, has become thicker and less flexible. This can happen due to previous surgeries, infections, or other conditions. It might not cause any symptoms, but sometimes it can make it harder for a doctor to do certain exams or procedures. It's important to know about it so that your healthcare provider can take it into account when planning any treatments or check-ups. A cervical disc herniation means that one of the cushions between the bones in your neck has moved out of place. Cervical spondylosis is a condition that affects the neck. It happens when the bones and discs in your neck start to wear down as you get older. This can cause neck pain and stiffness. Cervical spinal stenosis is a condition where the space around the spinal cord in your neck becomes narrow. This can put pressure on the spinal cord and nerves, which might cause pain, numbness, or weakness in your neck, shoulders, arms, or hands. Imagine the spinal cord as a highway for nerve signals, and stenosis is like a traffic jam that slows everything down. It's important to be aware of any symptoms you might have, like tingling or difficulty with balance, and talk to your doctor about them.

Cervical kyphosis is when the curve in your neck is not as it should be. Normally, your neck has a gentle curve that helps support your head and allows you to move it easily. A cervical vertebral fracture means that one of the bones in your neck has a crack or break. This can happen from an accident, like a fall or a car crash. A cervical rib is an extra rib that some people have. It grows from the base of your neck, just above your collarbone. Atlantoaxial instability is a condition where the first two bones in your neck, called the atlas and axis, are not as stable as they should be. When these bones move too much, it can cause pain or even affect the nerves in your neck. Degenerative Disc Disease is a condition where the discs in your spine, which act like cushions between the bones, start to wear down over time. This can happen as you get older. A thyroid nodule is a small lump or bump that can form in your thyroid gland, which is located in your neck. Most of the time, these nodules are not dangerous and don't cause any problems. A thyroid cyst is like a small, fluid-filled bubble that forms in your thyroid gland, which is located in your neck. Most of the time, these cysts are not harmful and don't cause any symptoms. They are often found by accident when you have an imaging test for something else. If the cyst is small and not causing any problems, doctors usually just keep an eye on it. A thyroid goiter is when your thyroid gland, which is in your neck, gets bigger than usual. The thyroid is like a small butterfly-shaped organ that helps control how your body uses energy. Most of the time, a goiter doesn't hurt, but it might make your neck look or feel different. If you notice any changes, it's a good idea to talk to a doctor.

Thyroiditis is when your thyroid gland, a small butterfly-shaped gland in your neck, becomes inflamed. This gland helps control your body's energy and metabolism. When it's inflamed, it might not work as well, which can make you feel tired, gain weight, or feel cold. Sometimes, it can also make your heart beat faster or make you feel nervous. It's important to pay attention to how you feel and talk to your doctor if you notice any changes. They can help you understand what's happening and what you can do to feel better.

Papillary thyroid carcinoma is a type of cancer that starts in the thyroid gland, which is a small, butterfly-shaped gland in your neck. This gland makes hormones that help control your body's energy and how it uses food. Papillary thyroid carcinoma is the most common type of thyroid cancer and usually grows slowly. It often affects people who are middle-aged, but it can happen at any age. The good news is that it is often treatable, especially when found early. Doctors use tests and treatments to help manage it and keep you healthy.

A multinodular goiter is when your thyroid gland, which is in your neck, has grown larger and has several lumps or nodules. The thyroid is important because it helps control how your body uses energy. Sometimes, these lumps don't cause any problems, but other times they can make your neck look bigger or cause trouble with swallowing or breathing. It's important to keep an eye on it to make sure it doesn't cause any issues. If you notice any changes or feel uncomfortable, let your doctor know.

Hyperthyroidism is when your thyroid gland, which is a small, butterfly-shaped gland in your neck, makes too much of a hormone that controls how your body uses energy. This can make your heart beat faster, make you feel nervous or anxious, and cause you to lose weight even if you are eating normally. You might also feel hot and sweaty or have trouble sleeping. It's like your body is running too fast. Doctors can help manage this condition with medicine or other treatments to help your body slow down and feel better.

A thyroid hematoma is when there is a collection of blood in the thyroid gland, which is located in your neck. This can happen due to an injury or after a medical procedure. It might cause swelling or a feeling of tightness in your neck. Sometimes, it can make it hard to breathe or swallow. Most of the time, the body will absorb the blood on its own, and the swelling will go down. It's important to keep an eye on any changes and let your doctor know if you feel worse.

Thyroid calcifications are tiny, hard spots that can form in your thyroid gland, which is a small, butterfly-shaped gland in your neck. These spots are made of calcium, a mineral that is important for strong bones and teeth. Sometimes, these calcifications are found by accident when you have an imaging test, like an ultrasound, for another reason. They usually don't cause any symptoms and are often harmless. However, in some cases, they can be a sign of a thyroid problem, so your doctor might want to keep an eye on them.

Tracheal stenosis means that the windpipe, which is the tube that carries air to your lungs, has become narrower than usual. This can make it harder to breathe because less air can pass through. Imagine trying to drink a thick milkshake through a thin straw; it takes more effort. This narrowing can happen because of injury, infection, or other reasons. It's important to pay attention to any breathing difficulties you might have, like feeling short of breath or wheezing, and let your doctor know about them.

A tracheal diverticulum is like a small pouch or pocket that forms on the windpipe, which is the tube that carries air to your lungs. It's kind of like a little bubble that sticks out from the side of the windpipe. Most of the time, people don't even know they have it because it doesn't cause any problems. It's usually found by accident when doctors are looking at scans for other reasons. If it does cause issues, it might make you cough or feel like you have a tickle in your throat.

Tracheomalacia is a condition where the windpipe, or trachea, is softer than usual. This can make it harder to breathe because the windpipe might collapse a bit when you breathe out. Imagine a straw that bends too easily when you try to drink from it. This can cause noisy breathing or a cough. Sometimes, it can make you feel like you're not getting enough air. It's important to be aware of this so you can manage any breathing problems that might come up.

A tracheal mass is a lump or growth in the windpipe, which is the tube that carries air to your lungs. This can sometimes make it hard to breathe or cause a cough. It's important to know that not all masses are cancerous; some can be benign, which means they are not harmful. Doctors usually find these masses during tests for other reasons. They might want to do more tests to understand what the mass is and how it might affect your health. Remember, it's okay to ask questions if you're worried.

Tracheal calcifications mean that there are small, hard deposits, like tiny rocks, in your windpipe. The windpipe is the tube that carries air to your lungs. A tracheoesophageal fistula is a condition where there is an abnormal connection between the tube that carries food to your stomach (esophagus) and the tube that carries air to your lungs (trachea). This can cause problems because food or liquid can go into your lungs instead of your stomach, which might make you cough or have trouble breathing. It is important to be careful when eating or drinking and to watch for any signs of coughing or breathing difficulties. If you notice these symptoms, it is important to let your doctor know.

Carotid artery stenosis means that one of the main blood vessels in your neck, called the carotid artery, is narrower than it should be. This can happen because of a buildup of fatty deposits, known as plaque, inside the artery walls. When the artery is too narrow, it can slow down or block the blood flow to your brain. This is important because your brain needs a steady supply of blood to work properly. If the blood flow is reduced, it might increase the risk of having a stroke, which is when part of the brain doesn't get enough blood and oxygen.

Jugular vein thrombosis means there's a blood clot in one of the veins in your neck. Veins are like tubes that carry blood back to your heart. When a clot forms, it can block the blood flow, which might cause swelling or pain in your neck. It's important to know about this because it can affect how blood moves in your body. Doctors can help manage it with treatments to dissolve the clot or prevent new ones from forming. It's like making sure a road is clear so cars can drive smoothly.

A vertebral artery dissection is when there is a small tear in one of the arteries in your neck that supplies blood to your brain. This can cause blood to leak into the wall of the artery, which might lead to a blockage or a clot. It's like when a garden hose gets a tiny hole, and water starts to leak out. This can sometimes cause headaches, neck pain, or dizziness. It's important to be aware of these symptoms so you can get help if needed.

An arteriovenous malformation, or AVM, is like a tangle of blood vessels in your body. Normally, blood flows from arteries to veins through tiny blood vessels called capillaries. But in an AVM, the blood skips the capillaries and goes straight from arteries to veins. This can cause problems because the blood vessels in an AVM are not as strong as normal ones. They might break and bleed, which can be dangerous. AVMs can happen anywhere in the body, but they are most serious when they are in the brain. Doctors can find them using special scans.

A carotid body tumor is a growth that happens near the carotid artery in your neck. This artery is important because it helps carry blood to your brain. The tumor is usually not cancerous, but it can grow and press on nearby structures, which might cause problems. You might feel a lump in your neck or have trouble swallowing. Sometimes, it can make you feel dizzy or have a fast heartbeat. It's important to keep an eye on it and talk to your doctor about what to do next.

A carotid artery aneurysm is when a part of the artery in your neck gets bigger than normal. This artery is important because it carries blood to your brain. When it gets bigger, it can be dangerous because it might burst or cause other problems. You might not feel anything at first, but it's important to know about it so doctors can keep an eye on it. They might do tests to see how big it is and decide if anything needs to be done to keep you safe.

Vertebral artery stenosis means that one of the arteries in your neck, which helps supply blood to your brain, is narrower than it should be. This can make it harder for blood to flow through. It's like when a garden hose gets pinched, and less water comes out. This narrowing can sometimes cause problems because your brain needs a steady supply of blood to work well. It's important to keep an eye on this condition to make sure your brain gets enough blood and stays healthy.

A carotid artery dissection is when there is a tear in one of the main arteries in your neck. These arteries are like big tubes that carry blood from your heart to your brain. When there is a tear, it can cause blood to leak into the wall of the artery, which might make it harder for blood to flow properly. This can sometimes lead to a headache, neck pain, or even a stroke. It's important to be aware of these symptoms so you can get help if needed.

A subclavian artery aneurysm is when a part of the artery near your collarbone gets bigger than normal. This artery is like a tube that carries blood from your heart to your arm. When it gets bigger, it can be a problem because it might burst or cause blood flow issues. You might not feel anything, but sometimes it can cause pain or swelling. It's important to keep an eye on it and talk to your doctor about what to do next to stay healthy.

Jugular venous dilatation means that the veins in your neck are larger than usual. These veins carry blood from your head back to your heart. When they are bigger, it might be because your heart is working harder than normal, or there could be a blockage. Sometimes, it can happen if you have been lying down for a long time or if you are holding your breath. It's important to keep an eye on it because it can be a sign of something else going on in your body.

A vocal cord polyp is like a small bump or growth on your vocal cords, which are the parts of your throat that help you talk. These polyps can make your voice sound different, like hoarse or scratchy, and sometimes it might be hard to speak loudly. They usually happen because of too much talking, yelling, or even from smoking. It's important to rest your voice and avoid things that can irritate your throat. Sometimes, doctors might suggest treatments to help make your voice better.

A uterine fibroid is a non-cancerous growth that can develop in the uterus, which is the part of a woman's body where a baby grows during pregnancy. These growths are quite common and are made up of muscle and fibrous tissue. They can vary in size and number. Some women may not even know they have them because they don't always cause symptoms. However, if they do cause symptoms, you might experience heavy periods, a feeling of fullness in your lower belly, or frequent urination. It's important to talk to your doctor if you have any concerns.

Prostatic hyperplasia is when the prostate gland, which is a small gland in men that helps make some of the fluid in semen, gets bigger. This is common as men get older. When the prostate gets bigger, it can press on the tube that carries urine out of the body, making it harder to pee. You might feel like you need to go to the bathroom more often, especially at night, or you might have trouble starting to pee. It's not cancer, but it can be annoying and sometimes needs treatment to help with the symptoms.

Pelvic lymphadenopathy means that the lymph nodes in your pelvic area are swollen. Lymph nodes are small, bean-shaped structures that are part of your immune system. They help your body fight infections and other diseases. When they swell, it can be because they are working hard to fight off an infection, or it could be due to other reasons. It's like when you have a sore throat and the glands in your neck get bigger. This swelling in your pelvic area might not cause any symptoms, but it's important to know about it.

A hemorrhagic cyst is a type of fluid-filled sac that can form in the body, often in the ovaries. Sometimes, these cysts can bleed, which is why they are called 'hemorrhagic.' This bleeding can cause pain or discomfort, but many times, these cysts go away on their own without causing any problems. It's like a small balloon filled with liquid that might have a little blood in it. If you feel any pain or notice anything unusual, it's important to let your doctor know so they can check it out.

A para-ovarian cyst is a fluid-filled sac that forms near the ovary. It's not actually part of the ovary, but it grows close to it. These cysts are usually harmless and don't cause any symptoms. They are often found by accident during an ultrasound or other imaging tests. Most of the time, they don't need any treatment and just stay the same size. However, if they get too big, they might cause some discomfort or pain. In such cases, a doctor might suggest removing them to prevent any problems.

A peritoneal cyst is like a small, fluid-filled bubble that forms in the lining of your abdomen, which is the area that holds your stomach and other organs. These cysts are usually harmless and don't cause any symptoms. They are often found by accident when doctors are looking at your belly for other reasons, like during an ultrasound or a CT scan. Most of the time, you don't need to worry about them, and they don't need any treatment. It's like having a tiny water balloon inside your tummy that doesn't bother you.

A simple hydrosalpinx is when one of the tubes that connect your ovaries to your uterus, called a fallopian tube, fills up with fluid. This can happen for different reasons, like an infection or a blockage. It usually doesn't cause any pain or problems, but sometimes it might make it harder to get pregnant. Doctors often find it by accident when they are looking at your belly with an ultrasound or other imaging tests. If you have any questions or concerns, it's a good idea to talk to your doctor.

An ovarian fibroma is a type of growth or lump that can form on the ovaries, which are part of the female reproductive system. These growths are usually not cancerous, meaning they don't spread to other parts of the body. They are made up of fibrous tissue, which is similar to the tissue that makes up tendons and ligaments. Most of the time, ovarian fibromas don't cause any symptoms and are found by accident during tests for other reasons. If they do cause symptoms, it might be things like feeling full quickly, bloating, or pain in the lower belly.

An endometrioma is a type of cyst that forms on the ovaries. It's like a small, fluid-filled sac that can cause pain, especially during your period. This happens because tissue similar to the lining inside your uterus starts growing outside of it, often on the ovaries. This can lead to discomfort and sometimes problems with having a baby. It's important to talk to your doctor if you have symptoms like pelvic pain or heavy periods, so they can help you feel better and manage the condition.

An ovarian dermoid is a type of growth that can form on a woman's ovary. It's like a small lump that can have different kinds of tissues inside, like hair, skin, or even teeth. These growths are usually not cancerous, which means they don't spread to other parts of the body. Most of the time, they don't cause any problems and might not even be noticed. However, sometimes they can cause pain or discomfort if they grow too big or twist around. It's important to keep an eye on them with regular check-ups.

Pelvic floor relaxation means that the muscles and tissues that support the organs in your pelvis, like your bladder and uterus, are not as strong as they should be. This can happen for many reasons, like having babies, getting older, or being overweight. When these muscles are weak, it might feel like there's pressure or a bulge in your lower belly. You might also have trouble controlling when you go to the bathroom. It's important to do exercises that can help make these muscles stronger, like Kegel exercises.

The vallecula is a small space in your throat, just above your voice box. Sometimes, one side of this space can look different from the other side. This is called an 'asymmetric appearance.' It might sound a bit worrying, but often it doesn't mean anything serious. It could be just the way your body is naturally. However, it's important to keep an eye on it, just in case it changes or causes any problems. If you notice any new symptoms like trouble swallowing or a sore throat, let your doctor know.

Perineural cysts, also known as Tarlov cysts, are small sacs filled with fluid that form around the nerves at the base of your spine. They are usually harmless and don't cause any symptoms. Most people don't even know they have them. However, if they grow larger, they might press on nearby nerves and cause pain or discomfort. It's like having a small balloon filled with water near your nerves. Doctors often find these cysts by accident when looking at your spine for other reasons. If they don't bother you, they usually don't need treatment.

An inguinal hernia happens when a part of your intestine pushes through a weak spot in your lower belly area, near your groin. It might look like a small bulge or lump, and you might feel some discomfort or pain, especially when you cough, bend over, or lift something heavy. It's like when a balloon gets a small bump because the air inside is pushing out. Sometimes, it can go away when you lie down. It's important to be careful and avoid heavy lifting to prevent it from getting worse.
